<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1245</anchor>  <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>dan-ghica</addr>  <route>dan-ghica.xml</route>   <title>Dan R. Ghica</title> <meta name="external">https://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~drg/</meta><meta name="institution">University of Birmingham</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1246</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-0048</addr>  <route>axt-0048.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>23</day></date> <authors><author><link href="dan-ghica.xml" type="local">Dan R. Ghica</link></author> </authors> <title>Arena</title> <meta name="source"><b>Defn. 2</b> from the lecture notes</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  An <b>arena</b> consists of:
  <ul>    <li>A set <tex>M</tex>, called the set of <em>moves</em>.</li>    <li>A subset <tex>Q  \subseteq  M</tex>, called the set of <em>questions</em>.</li>    <li>A subset <tex>O  \subseteq  M</tex>, called the set of <em>opponent moves</em>.</li>    <li>A subset <tex>I  \subseteq  Q  \cap  O</tex>, called the set of <em>initial moves</em>.</li>    <li>      A relation <tex>{-}  \vdash  {-}  \subseteq  M  \times  M</tex> satisfying the
      conditions
      <ol>        <li><tex>m  \in  Q</tex>,</li>        <li><tex>m  \in  O</tex> iff <tex>n  \in  P</tex>, and</li>        <li><tex>n  \notin  I</tex>.</li>      </ol>    </li>  </ul></p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1247</anchor>   <addr>axt-0047</addr>  <route>axt-0047.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>23</day></date> <authors><author><link href="dan-ghica.xml" type="local">Dan R. Ghica</link></author> </authors> <title>Idea of full abstraction</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A denotational semantics for a programming language is called <em>fully
  abstract</em> if the notion of semantic equality that it induces coincides with
  the notion of observational equivalence in the language. In other words,
  we have
  <tex display="block">\llbracket   t_1   \rrbracket  =  \llbracket   t_2   \rrbracket \  \leftrightarrow \  t_1  \equiv  t_2,</tex>  where <tex>\equiv</tex> denotes observational equivalence.
</p></mainmatter> </tree></contributions> <context/> <related/> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>